<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="mlp-planning">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>product</group>
    <domain>product-manager</domain>
    <summary>Four-layer audit framework for evolving MVP that users find "fine" into one they love, identifying delight gaps and generating polish backlog ranked by Pain×Frequency×Visibility.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>mlp</tag>
      <tag>product-polish</tag>
      <tag>retention</tag>
      <tag>delight</tag>
      <tag>mvp-evolution</tag>
    </tags>
    <category>product</category>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-29</created>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>MLP Planning</title>

    <summary>Minimum Lovable Product planning: a four-layer audit framework (Functional → Reliable → Usable → Delightful) for evolving an MVP that users find "fine" into one they love and recommend. The process identifies delight gaps by clustering feedback where the core job is done but the emotion is missing, then generates a polish backlog ranked by Pain × Frequency × Visibility. MLP threshold: all core features score 4+ on all four layers.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>MVP validates the core assumption but often fails to retain users in crowded categories where competitors already clear the "viable" bar. Users leave not because the product doesn't work, but because it lacks emotional connection. Adding delight (speed, simplicity, personality, anticipation, celebration) on top of a working foundation is the lowest-CAC retention investment because it converts activation to word-of-mouth.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>MVP shipped with measurable activation but Day-30 retention plateaus below 25-30%.</item>
        <item>NPS &lt; 30 or churn surveys show users finish the core job but describe the product as "fine" or "okay".</item>
        <item>Retention curve flattens after week 2 — function works, emotion missing.</item>
        <item>About to enter a paid acquisition phase: every dollar spent on a non-lovable product compounds CAC waste.</item>
        <item>Pre-launch in a category where competitors already cleared the "viable" bar.</item>
        <item>Refactor or redesign sprint with explicit budget for polish, copy, micro-interactions.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Pre-MVP — there is nothing to make lovable yet. Use `mvp-scoping` or `minimum-product-frameworks` first.</item>
        <item>Product-market fit not validated — adding delight before demand signal hides the real problem.</item>
        <item>Infrastructure or B2B plumbing where users only interact via API — delight surface is too small.</item>
        <item>Capacity-constrained team mid-incident — Layer 1 and 2 regressions trump delight work.</item>
        <item>Hard-deadline compliance or regulatory features — polish budget is zero until shipped.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="four-layer-model">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>All core features must score 4+ on all four layers before claiming MLP status. Delight (Layer 4) cannot compensate for gaps in Functional (1), Reliable (2), or Usable (3).</statement>
        <rationale>Delight applied to a broken or confusing product amplifies the frustration — users notice the personality of a product that still crashes or loses their data more acutely than they would on a dull product.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Layer 1 — Functional: core job gets done, no blocking bugs, acceptable performance.</item>
        <item>Layer 2 — Reliable: consistent experience, error handling, edge cases covered, works as expected every time.</item>
        <item>Layer 3 — Usable: easy to learn, efficient to use, minimal friction, good defaults.</item>
        <item>Layer 4 — Delightful: emotional satisfaction, surprising moments, premium feel, shareable moments.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="mvp-vs-mlp">
      <list>
        <item>MVP goal: validate. MLP goal: retain and generate word of mouth.</item>
        <item>MVP focus: functionality. MLP focus: experience on top of that functionality.</item>
        <item>MVP emotion: "it works." MLP emotion: "I love it."</item>
        <item>MVP word of mouth: unlikely. MLP word of mouth: likely.</item>
      </list>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>MLP = MVP + delight. Not more features — better experience of existing features. Audit before building; most products reach MLP by polishing the core, not by adding functionality.</statement>
        <rationale>Adding features to a sub-MLP product increases surface area for friction without addressing the root cause: the existing interactions are not good enough to generate retention.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="five-delight-categories">
      <list>
        <item>Speed: faster than expected — instant search results, sub-100ms interactions.</item>
        <item>Simplicity: easier than expected — one-click checkout, zero-configuration defaults.</item>
        <item>Personality: unexpected charm — clever copywriting, brand-consistent micro-copy.</item>
        <item>Anticipation: knows what users need before they ask — smart defaults, pre-filled fields.</item>
        <item>Celebration: acknowledges user success — confetti on completion, "you've earned $X" summaries.</item>
      </list>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Require at least one delight idea per category from the audit before picking the sprint focus. Agents default to Personality and Celebration; Speed and Anticipation are underrepresented without forcing.</statement>
        <rationale>Speed is the cheapest and most underrated delight lever — performance budgets on the core action produce retention lift with zero UX redesign cost. Forcing coverage prevents category tunnel-vision.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="polish-priority-formula">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Score each polish task as Pain × Frequency × Visibility. If any factor is hard to estimate, use additive scoring (Pain + Frequency + Visibility) to avoid a single zero zeroing out a real opportunity.</statement>
        <rationale>The multiplicative formula breaks down when any dimension is genuinely uncertain — a low-frequency interaction that causes severe pain still deserves consideration, but a zero in Frequency produces a score of zero multiplicatively.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="five-step-planning-process">
      <list>
        <item>Step 1 — Audit: score each core feature 1-5 on all four layers using current user verbatims and session replay as evidence. Do not score against aspirations.</item>
        <item>Step 2 — Identify opportunities: cluster negative-but-not-blocking feedback ("works but underwhelming") by delight category.</item>
        <item>Step 3 — Prioritize: rank by Pain × Frequency × Visibility, max 12 items.</item>
        <item>Step 4 — Define MLP criteria: write numeric completion criteria before starting (e.g., Day-30 retention target, NPS target, core action time budget).</item>
        <item>Step 5 — Plan the gap: build a sprint-by-sprint polish backlog, time-box each delight sprint at 2 weeks maximum.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="note-taking-app-example">
      <example type="good">
        <note>MVP state: create, edit, delete notes; basic formatting; functional but bland. Day-30 retention: 18%. NPS: 30.</note>
        <note>Layer 2 (Reliable): added auto-save with visual confirmation. Eliminated "did it save?" anxiety.</note>
        <note>Layer 3 (Usable): added keyboard shortcuts for common actions; quick capture from any screen.</note>
        <note>Layer 4 (Delight/Speed): smooth animations on state transitions; sub-50ms search.</note>
        <note>Layer 4 (Delight/Personality): "Zen mode" for focused writing; clever empty states with contextual prompts.</note>
        <note>Layer 4 (Delight/Celebration): satisfying sound on note save (opt-in).</note>
        <note>Result: Day-30 retention increased 40% (from 18% to 25%); NPS from 30 to 55. Core action time decreased 30%.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="invoicing-tool-example">
      <example type="good">
        <note>MVP state: create invoices, send to clients. Functional but clunky. Core action (send invoice) takes 4 minutes. Day-30 retention: 35%.</note>
        <note>Layer 2 (Reliable): payment confirmation notifications with push and email fallback.</note>
        <note>Layer 3 (Usable): templates pre-filled from past invoices; client auto-fill from contact database.</note>
        <note>Layer 4 (Delight/Celebration): animated celebration screen on payment received with amount summary.</note>
        <note>Layer 4 (Delight/Anticipation): "You've earned $X this month" dashboard tile; proactive invoice reminder suggestions.</note>
        <note>Result: users create 2x more invoices per month; NPS 60; core action time reduced from 4 minutes to 90 seconds.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="common-mistakes">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Adding more features to an MVP instead of polishing existing ones to MLP threshold.</description>
        <reason>Feature addition expands surface area for friction without addressing the root retention problem. Most MVPs reach MLP by improving the core 3 features to Layer 4, not by adding a 4th feature.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Surface-level polish (new colors, marketing copy) while ignoring interaction quality (latency, defaults, error recovery).</description>
        <reason>Visual polish is visible but does not compound; interaction quality (speed, anticipation, recovery) affects every session and compounds with usage frequency.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Skipping numeric MLP completion criteria before starting delight work.</description>
        <reason>Without exit criteria, "MLP" expands indefinitely — teams keep polishing without shipping. The criteria are the commitment mechanism that ends the sprint.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Generic delight (confetti everywhere) not tailored to the user persona.</description>
        <reason>B2B enterprise users find confetti unprofessional; Japanese users find animated celebrations intrusive. Delight must be calibrated to the specific persona's emotional context.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>Drive MLP planning as a 3-phase agent loop: (1) Audit phase — feed the agent product analytics export + recent NPS/churn comments and ask it to fill the 4-layer scorecard per feature; (2) Discovery phase — agent surfaces delight opportunities by clustering negative-but-not-blocking feedback ("works but underwhelming") and matching them to the 5 delight categories (Speed/Simplicity/Personality/Anticipation/Celebration); (3) Planning phase — agent generates a polish backlog ranked by Pain × Frequency × Visibility, and writes the MLP plan using templates. Human-in-the-loop required at the discovery → planning handoff (delight choices are brand decisions, not data decisions).</p>
    </section>

    <section name="recommended-subagents">
      <list>
        <item>faion-mlp-gap-finder-agent — domain-specific agent; audits MVP, scores 4 layers, surfaces gaps. Invoke for the audit phase.</item>
        <item>faion-sdd-executor-agent — once polish tasks are defined as SDD tasks, drives sequential execution with quality gates. Use after MLP plan is approved.</item>
        <item>brainstorm skill — multi-agent diverge/converge for the delight-opportunity step. Single-agent ideation tends to converge on copywriting; brainstorm forces broader categories.</item>
        <item>user-researcher knowledge (pro/ux/user-researcher/) — pull qualitative interview methods for validating delight hypotheses before building.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="prompt-patterns">
      <example type="good">
        <note>MLP-gap-finder prompt:</note>
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
You are MLP-gap-finder. Inputs: <feature list>, <analytics CSV>, <NPS verbatims>.
For each feature, score 1-5 on Functional/Reliable/Usable/Delightful using the rubric below.
Output: JSON array [{feature, scores: {f,r,u,d}, evidence: [verbatim_id...]}].
Do NOT invent scores; cite at least one evidence_id per non-default score.
        ]]></code>
      </example>
      <example type="good">
        <note>Delight-prioritizer prompt:</note>
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
You are delight-prioritizer. Input: gap report from previous step.
Cluster gaps by delight category (Speed/Simplicity/Personality/Anticipation/Celebration).
Reject any "delight" idea that requires lifting Layer 1-3 scores below 4.
Output: ranked backlog with Pain×Frequency×Visibility, max 12 items.
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <list>
        <item>Agents inflate Functional/Reliable scores when trained on internal docs — internal docs always describe the happy path. Force grounding on session replays or support tickets, not docs.</item>
        <item>LLMs collapse "Usable" and "Delightful" because the language overlaps. Explicitly forbid scoring Delight ≥ 4 unless the agent can quote a user verbatim using emotional language ("love", "amazing", "I showed my friend").</item>
        <item>"Add personality" prompts produce on-brand-but-generic copy at scale. Constrain agents with brand voice samples and a banned-phrases list (no "delight", "magic", "seamless", "effortless").</item>
        <item>Without a holdout cohort instruction, agents recommend stacked changes that make causal attribution impossible. Always require: "ship one delight intervention per cohort per week."</item>
        <item>Agents will recommend animations that fail accessibility — add an explicit a11y constraint to the prompt and link pro/ux/accessibility-specialist/.</item>
        <item>Delight-opportunity clustering by LLM tends to favor visual/auditory categories (Celebration, Personality) over harder ones (Speed, Anticipation). Force minimum coverage: at least 1 idea per category.</item>
        <item>Human-in-the-loop checkpoints: (a) after audit scores — review for evidence grounding; (b) after delight-category clustering — brand approval; (c) before flag rollout — legal/compliance for any data-driven personalization.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="cli-tools-and-services">
      <list>
        <item>posthog CLI — pull retention cohorts, funnel data for the audit (npm i -g posthog-cli)</item>
        <item>amplitude-api — export event data for delight-moment analysis (pip amplitude-analytics)</item>
        <item>gh (GitHub CLI) — create polish-backlog issues from agent JSON output</item>
        <item>linear CLI (@linear/sdk) — push MLP backlog into Linear with Pain/Freq/Vis labels</item>
        <item>productboard-cli (community) — sync delight opportunities to Productboard</item>
        <item>dovetail API — pull tagged interview snippets as evidence</item>
        <item>delighted API / wootric — NPS verbatim export, segment by score</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="saas-services">
      <list>
        <item>PostHog (SaaS + OSS) — retention curves, feature-flag-gated delight rollouts</item>
        <item>Amplitude (SaaS) — best for funnel/cohort math; Pathfinder identifies friction points</item>
        <item>Mixpanel (SaaS) — solid for activation funnel; impact reports for delight A/B</item>
        <item>Productboard (SaaS) — tag delight opportunities against features</item>
        <item>Linear (SaaS) — stable target for polish backlog; cycle planning fits delight sprints</item>
        <item>Maze (SaaS) — run usability tests on delight prototypes pre-build</item>
        <item>Dovetail (SaaS) — tag-driven theme extraction from user interviews</item>
        <item>Pendo / Appcues (SaaS) — onboarding/empty-state delight delivery without code deploys</item>
        <item>Hotjar / FullStory (SaaS) — session replay to find dull moments humans miss</item>
        <item>LottieFiles (OSS + SaaS) — source library for celebration animations agents can wire in</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Anchor each layer score with a concrete rubric example before scoring (e.g., "Delight=5 means at least one user voluntarily shared a screenshot in the last 30 days").</item>
        <item>Score features against current user verbatims, not against the team's aspirations. Pull at least 5 evidence quotes per non-trivial score.</item>
        <item>Treat performance budgets (TTI, p95 latency on the core action) as Layer 4 work, not infra work — speed is the cheapest, most underrated form of delight.</item>
        <item>Run a delight sprint as a fixed time-box (max 2 weeks) on a single workflow. Cross-cutting "polish everywhere" loses focus and produces nothing shippable.</item>
        <item>Ship delight behind a feature flag with a 50/50 split for the first week. Confetti on payment is funny once and annoying on day 30 — flag it so you can dial back without a deploy.</item>
        <item>Pair every delight feature with a kill-switch metric (rage-click rate, time-to-dismiss). Delight that increases task completion time without retention lift is a regression.</item>
        <item>Write the MLP completion criteria BEFORE starting work. Without numeric exit criteria, "MLP" expands until the team burns out.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="references">
      <list>
        <item>Aarron Walter, "Designing for Emotion" (A Book Apart, 2011) — foundational source for emotional design hierarchy.</item>
        <item>Lance Wilson, "Why MVP is dead and MLP is the way" — bringing the MLP term into product vocabulary.</item>
        <item>Jared Spool, "The $300 Million Button" — case study on usability-as-delight.</item>
        <item>Kano Model (Noriaki Kano) — adjacent framework that maps to Layer 4 "delighters".</item>
        <item>PostHog product analytics docs: posthog.com/docs/product-analytics/retention</item>
        <item>Amplitude Pathfinder: amplitude.com/blog/pathfinder</item>
        <item>WCAG 2.2 Reduced Motion: w3.org/WAI/WCAG22/Understanding/animation-from-interactions</item>
        <item>Related methodologies: mvp-scoping/, minimum-product-frameworks/, release-planning/, product-analytics/</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/mlp-plan.md" purpose="Full MLP planning document: current state, goal, feature audit, delight opportunities, polish backlog, completion criteria, measurement plan"/>
      <template path="templates/delight-sprint.md" purpose="Single-workflow delight sprint: scope, current experience, target experience, tasks, success criteria"/>
    </templates>

    <scripts>
      <script path="scripts/audit-to-backlog.sh" purpose="Converts mlp-gap-finder JSON audit output into Linear issues with Pain×Freq×Vis priority scores"/>
    </scripts>
  </content>
</methodology>
